l as sexist and humiliating—dimensions. Drawing on narrative therapy, dialogic theory, and multisited ethnography, The Anorexic Self cultivates a less judgmental and more self-reflexive way of relating to ourselves, others, and societies in which we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAnorexia nervosaxSocial aspects. 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aFeminist theory. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Feminist. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aSociology : Sociology of Women. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079147830140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791478301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791478301/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles